NNAAMMEE
     ssmmttppccttll - control the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol daemon

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
     ssmmttppccttll _c_o_m_m_a_n_d [_a_r_g_u_m_e_n_t _._._.]

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
     The ssmmttppccttll program controls smtpd(8).  Commands may be abbreviated to
     the minimum unambiguous prefix; for example, sshh ss for sshhooww ssttaattss.

     The following commands are available:

     lloogg bbrriieeff
             Disable verbose debug logging.

     lloogg vveerrbboossee
             Enable verbose debug logging.

     ppaauussee iinnccoommiinngg
             Temporarily stop accepting incoming sessions.

     ppaauussee llooccaall
             Temporarily stop deliveries to local users.

     ppaauussee oouuttggooiinngg
             Temporarily stop relaying and deliveries to remote users.

     rreemmoovvee _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_u_i_d | _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_i_d
             Removes a single message, or all messages with the same message
             ID.

     rreessuummee iinnccoommiinngg
             Resume accepting incoming sessions.

     rreessuummee llooccaall
             Resume deliveries to local users.

     rreessuummee oouuttggooiinngg
             Resume relaying and deliveries to remote users.

     sscchheedduullee _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_u_i_d | _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_i_d
             Marks a single message, or all messages with the same message ID,
             as ready for immediate delivery.

     sshhooww qquueeuuee
             Displays information concerning envelopes that are currently in a
             queue.

     sshhooww rruunnqquueeuuee
             Displays information concerning envelopes that are scheduled for
             delivery.

     sshhooww ssttaattss
             Displays runtime statistics concerning smtpd(8).

     When ssmmttppdd receives a message, it generates a _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_i_d for the message,
     and one _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_u_i_d per recipient.  The _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_i_d consists of a
     timestamp followed by a random identifier that is guaranteed to be unique
     on the host system.  The _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_u_i_d consists of the _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_i_d followed
     by a random identifier that is also guaranteed to be unique between
     recipients of the same message.

     A command which specifies a _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_i_d applies to all recipients of a
     message; a command which specifies a _m_e_s_s_a_g_e_-_u_i_d applies to a specific
     recipient of a message.

